{
  "texts": [
    "Figure 3C compares model predictions to patient apparent brightness ratings (on a 1-10 scale) across pulse trains that vary in pulse width (0.2-1 ms), frequency (5-100 Hz), pulse-train duration (0.2-1 s) and amplitude (0.2-5 mA) in three surface electrodes 35.",
    "There is a strong correlation between simulation predictions and patient data (r(42) = 0.771, p < 0.0001).",
    "Thus, the data from Fig. 3, collated across a wide variety of studies, supports the notion that a basic model describing the transformation from pulse trains to perceptual intensity over time can successfully predict both thresholds and brightness ratings across a wide range of pulse train parameters, electrode locations and sizes.",
    "In practice, the goal of most stimulation protocols is to maximize charge efficiency in order to maximize battery life: our model predicts little benefit for increasing pulse width durations beyond 0.4 ms, or stimulation frequencies above 64 Hz.",
    "Our model also successfully predicts phosphene size as a function of amplitude."
  ]
}